  "text": "The higher H1 frequency at C-V transition in prevocalic position presumably transposes the higher amplitude of the release in geminate stops in normal speech. As already stated, this attribute can be the sole distinctive cue to gemination for spoken utterance-initial voiceless stops, since closure duration cannot be acoustically implemented. The higher amplitude of the release in spoken forms is generally considered to be an automatic outcome of the longer duration of the stops. That is, the higher air pressure rise behind the closure after long consonants results automatically in higher or stronger amplitude of the release [CITATION_1] . This aerodynamic account cannot apply for our whistling data, suggesting that this attribute is probably actively controlled and does not solely result from implementational effects of the primary duration attribute. Higher H1 frequency values for whistled geminates may be viewed as an enhancing correlate, which increases the perceptual distance between singletons and geminates. This correlate is probably computed online as opposed to the defining attribute. It is introduced precisely because word-initial context puts the defining attribute in jeopardy, as duration is not perceptually recoverable in this position. This also implies that speakers/whistlers have a tacit knowledge of the physical pressures that shape lexical forms.",
